00:02:32.200 --> 00:02:34.510 align:middle line:84%
the most overwhelming
person you've ever met?

00:02:34.510 --> 00:02:36.500 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Well, it
was Michael Jackson.

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:37.040 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Ah!

00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:39.290 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: And you would
think Michael Jackson, just

00:02:39.290 --> 00:02:40.980 align:middle line:90%
a superficial pop star, right?

00:02:40.980 --> 00:02:44.220 align:middle line:84%
No, he wasn't a
superficial pop star.

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:47.560 align:middle line:84%
When I was 10,
there were two rules

00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:48.840 align:middle line:90%
that attracted me to science.

00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:50.850 align:middle line:84%
Rule number one was
the truth at any price,

00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:52.830 align:middle line:84%
including the
price of your life.

00:02:52.830 --> 00:02:55.667 align:middle line:84%
You'd be willing to give up
your life on behalf of a truth.

00:02:55.667 --> 00:02:58.000 align:middle line:84%
Rule number two was look at
things right under your nose

00:02:58.000 --> 00:02:59.458 align:middle line:84%
as if you've never
seen them before

00:02:59.458 --> 00:03:00.800 align:middle line:90%
and then proceed from there.

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:04.040 align:middle line:84%
Michael Jackson embodied the
first two rules of science

00:03:04.040 --> 00:03:07.990 align:middle line:84%
in a way I've never seen from
another human being in my life

00:03:07.990 --> 00:03:10.440 align:middle line:90%
and never even expected to see.

00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:12.745 align:middle line:90%
He was beyond human.

00:03:12.745 --> 00:03:14.950 align:middle line:84%
But beyond human in
a way we should all

00:03:14.950 --> 00:03:17.410 align:middle line:90%
aspire to be beyond human.

00:03:17.410 --> 00:03:19.527 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: He's sorely
missed, sorely missed.

00:03:19.527 --> 00:03:20.360 align:middle line:90%
What a great talent!

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:21.625 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: He's sorely missed.

00:03:21.625 --> 00:03:24.040 align:middle line:84%
And two weeks ago,
there was another person

00:03:24.040 --> 00:03:26.890 align:middle line:84%
that I've spent a little bit
of time with-- Elon Musk.

00:03:26.890 --> 00:03:29.720 align:middle line:10%
Elon Musk is the
head of SpaceX, which

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:31.530 align:middle line:10%
is the only private
company, in fact, it's

00:03:31.530 --> 00:03:34.170 align:middle line:10%
the only company in the
world right now in America

00:03:34.170 --> 00:03:36.990 align:middle line:10%
that can get Americans to
space in American vehicles,

00:03:36.990 --> 00:03:38.340 align:middle line:10%
it can get American cargo to--

00:03:38.340 --> 00:03:39.900 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Heads up, Tesla
Motors came up with that idea.

00:03:39.900 --> 00:03:41.890 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: --and Tesla
Motors, exactly.

00:03:41.890 --> 00:03:44.640 align:middle line:84%
And I said to somebody,
one of the reasons

00:03:44.640 --> 00:03:46.070 align:middle line:84%
that I was attracted
to Elon, one

00:03:46.070 --> 00:03:49.510 align:middle line:84%
of the reasons I had four phone
calls with him is because here

00:03:49.510 --> 00:03:52.392 align:middle line:84%
I've spent my whole life looking
for the forces of history.

00:03:52.392 --> 00:03:54.600 align:middle line:84%
And I could see that Elon
was one of those people who

00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:57.177 align:middle line:84%
will be remembered
150 years from now.

00:03:57.177 --> 00:03:59.010 align:middle line:84%
And the person on the
other end of the phone

00:03:59.010 --> 00:04:01.290 align:middle line:84%
said, wait a minute, you're
forgetting about somebody,

00:04:01.290 --> 00:04:02.300 align:middle line:90%
aren't you?

00:04:02.300 --> 00:04:04.130 align:middle line:90%
And I wanted to know who.

00:04:04.130 --> 00:04:05.250 align:middle line:90%
He said, Michael Jackson.

00:04:05.250 --> 00:04:08.410 align:middle line:84%
Now, if Michael Jackson is
able to survive for 150 years,

00:04:08.410 --> 00:04:10.080 align:middle line:90%
he does set a new standard.

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:12.640 align:middle line:84%
When you come to
understand how deeply,

00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:13.830 align:middle line:90%
how intensely he could--

00:04:13.830 --> 00:04:16.420 align:middle line:84%
Well, one day, we
were at his brother

00:04:16.420 --> 00:04:18.410 align:middle line:84%
Marlon's pool house,
a little house

00:04:18.410 --> 00:04:20.420 align:middle line:84%
out in the back
of the main house.

00:04:20.420 --> 00:04:22.082 align:middle line:84%
And it's a house
much smaller than--

00:04:22.082 --> 00:04:23.790 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But, was this
before, Howard, he

00:04:23.790 --> 00:04:26.215 align:middle line:84%
started doing all this
heavy plastic surgery?

00:04:26.215 --> 00:04:27.090 align:middle line:90%
Or what that ongoing?

00:04:27.090 --> 00:04:30.060 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: It was, no, he looked
like a perfectly normal person

00:04:30.060 --> 00:04:30.970 align:middle line:90%
at that point.

00:04:30.970 --> 00:04:33.550 align:middle line:84%
And so they've got
an appointment,

00:04:33.550 --> 00:04:36.790 align:middle line:84%
it's a little room, and there's
a pool table in the middle.

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:38.520 align:middle line:84%
And there are all
these arcade games

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:40.980 align:middle line:84%
around the sides of the
room, the kinds of games

00:04:40.980 --> 00:04:43.530 align:middle line:90%
only billionaires can afford.

00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:46.630 align:middle line:84%
And the guys had a meeting
with the art director

00:04:46.630 --> 00:04:48.510 align:middle line:90%
from CBS Records.

00:04:48.510 --> 00:04:50.620 align:middle line:84%
Well, Michael came
shortly before the meeting

00:04:50.620 --> 00:04:51.816 align:middle line:90%
with the art director.

00:04:51.816 --> 00:04:53.190 align:middle line:84%
I had learned a
lesson, I grew up

00:04:53.190 --> 00:04:55.870 align:middle line:84%
among Guinea pigs and laboratory
rats, not human beings,

00:04:55.870 --> 00:04:57.850 align:middle line:84%
so I don't understand
human rituals.

00:04:57.850 --> 00:04:59.731 align:middle line:84%
But I had through
observation noticed

00:04:59.731 --> 00:05:01.230 align:middle line:84%
that when you meet
a new person, you

00:05:01.230 --> 00:05:02.604 align:middle line:84%
walk over, you
put your hand out,

00:05:02.604 --> 00:05:04.220 align:middle line:84%
and you say, hi,
your name is Howard.

00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:06.020 align:middle line:84%
So the screen door
began to open.

00:05:06.020 --> 00:05:07.940 align:middle line:84%
I walked over and
put my hand out,

00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:09.450 align:middle line:84%
and said, "Hi, my
name is Howard."

00:05:09.450 --> 00:05:12.140 align:middle line:84%
I had read thousands of
articles on Michael by then.

00:05:12.140 --> 00:05:13.756 align:middle line:84%
They all said he
was a bubble baby.

00:05:13.756 --> 00:05:14.380 align:middle line:90%
They all said--

00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:15.390 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: He didn't touch people?

00:05:15.390 --> 00:05:16.848 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: No, that
he would retract,

00:05:16.848 --> 00:05:18.780 align:middle line:84%
that he'd shy away
from your hand.

00:05:18.780 --> 00:05:20.230 align:middle line:90%
No, he put out his hand.

00:05:20.230 --> 00:05:22.860 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't a hard grip,
it wasn't a soft grip.

00:05:22.860 --> 00:05:24.030 align:middle line:90%
It was a normal grip.

00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:25.220 align:middle line:90%
It was a human grip.

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:26.990 align:middle line:90%
And said, "Hi, I'm Michael."

00:05:26.990 --> 00:05:31.040 align:middle line:84%
And I had a press release I
wanted to get him to approve.

00:05:31.040 --> 00:05:31.860 align:middle line:90%
I told him.

00:05:31.860 --> 00:05:34.330 align:middle line:84%
He said, let's go up
to the second floor.

00:05:34.330 --> 00:05:37.220 align:middle line:84%
The second floor was just jammed
with equipment-- amplifiers,

00:05:37.220 --> 00:05:39.340 align:middle line:84%
keyboards, no place,
really, to sit.

00:05:39.340 --> 00:05:41.360 align:middle line:90%
So we sat on amplifiers.

00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:43.040 align:middle line:90%
I read him the press release.

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:46.270 align:middle line:84%
And as I read it to him,
he started sliding down

00:05:46.270 --> 00:05:48.290 align:middle line:84%
on the amplifier like
this, and his face

00:05:48.290 --> 00:05:51.250 align:middle line:84%
got more and more-- I
couldn't quite tell what.

00:05:51.250 --> 00:05:55.750 align:middle line:84%
And then, when I finished, he
said, "Did you write that?"

00:05:55.750 --> 00:05:56.480 align:middle line:90%
Yes, I had.

00:05:56.480 --> 00:05:58.620 align:middle line:90%
He said, "That was beautiful."

00:05:58.620 --> 00:06:00.574 align:middle line:84%
In other words, Michael
could see the craft

00:06:00.574 --> 00:06:01.615 align:middle line:90%
in the tiniest of things.

00:06:01.615 --> 00:06:03.040 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's right,
and it affected him.

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:03.660 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yeah.

00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:07.070 align:middle line:84%
And then we went down to
be with the art director.

00:06:07.070 --> 00:06:08.570 align:middle line:84%
The art director
came in with five

00:06:08.570 --> 00:06:10.810 align:middle line:84%
of the most gorgeous
portfolios you've ever seen.

00:06:10.810 --> 00:06:13.240 align:middle line:84%
These are America's
five top artists.

00:06:13.240 --> 00:06:15.272 align:middle line:84%
And she slid them across
the pool table at us.

00:06:15.272 --> 00:06:17.230 align:middle line:84%
Michael and I were standing
next to each other,

00:06:17.230 --> 00:06:19.370 align:middle line:84%
and the brothers were
standing around us.

00:06:19.370 --> 00:06:22.560 align:middle line:84%
When Michael started
to open the first page

00:06:22.560 --> 00:06:26.730 align:middle line:84%
of the first portfolio, he only
got an inch open, and he went,

00:06:26.730 --> 00:06:27.890 align:middle line:90%
oh.

00:06:27.890 --> 00:06:30.410 align:middle line:84%
And then he opened
another inch-- oh.

00:06:30.410 --> 00:06:32.026 align:middle line:90%
And then more-- oh.

00:06:32.026 --> 00:06:33.900 align:middle line:84%
And what you could feel
in his body language,

00:06:33.900 --> 00:06:35.440 align:middle line:84%
because he was
going orgasmic, it

00:06:35.440 --> 00:06:37.902 align:middle line:84%
was as if he were having the
ultimate sexual experience,

00:06:37.902 --> 00:06:39.360 align:middle line:84%
but he was having
it aesthetically.

00:06:39.360 --> 00:06:40.010 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: In his head.

00:06:40.010 --> 00:06:40.593 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yeah.

00:06:40.593 --> 00:06:43.390 align:middle line:84%
And you could feel
that Michael was

00:06:43.390 --> 00:06:45.540 align:middle line:84%
seeing the infinite in
the tiniest of things.

00:06:45.540 --> 00:06:47.540 align:middle line:84%
Everything that William
Blake ever talked about,

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:49.810 align:middle line:84%
when he talked about seeing
the world in a grain of sand--

00:06:49.810 --> 00:06:50.976 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Uh-ha, right there.

00:06:50.976 --> 00:06:52.050 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Right there.

00:06:52.050 --> 00:06:53.980 align:middle line:90%
And it was so visceral.

00:06:53.980 --> 00:06:56.780 align:middle line:84%
It took over
Michael's entire body.

00:06:56.780 --> 00:06:58.640 align:middle line:84%
So that second law
of science-- look

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:00.340 align:middle line:84%
at things right under your
nose as if you've never

00:07:00.340 --> 00:07:01.714 align:middle line:84%
seen them before
and then proceed

00:07:01.714 --> 00:07:04.650 align:middle line:84%
from there-- that's a
law of awe and wonder.

00:07:04.650 --> 00:07:08.330 align:middle line:84%
Michael was awe
embodied and personified

00:07:08.330 --> 00:07:10.910 align:middle line:84%
in a way I had
never, ever imagined

00:07:10.910 --> 00:07:13.110 align:middle line:84%
a human on the face of
planet Earth could be.

00:07:13.110 --> 00:07:15.670 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And he gave it
when he was on stage.

00:07:15.670 --> 00:07:16.300 align:middle line:90%
He gave it.

00:07:16.300 --> 00:07:19.240 align:middle line:84%
Which reminds me of what
happened several weeks ago--

00:07:19.240 --> 00:07:19.950 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yeah?

00:07:19.950 --> 00:07:24.120 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: The hologram of
Michael Jackson at a concert.

00:07:24.120 --> 00:07:27.810 align:middle line:84%
It looked like he
was really there.

00:07:27.810 --> 00:07:29.907 align:middle line:84%
Are we going too
far with technology?

00:07:29.907 --> 00:07:31.740 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: No, we're not
going too far at all,

00:07:31.740 --> 00:07:34.399 align:middle line:84%
because, look, Michael's
ultimate task, for example,

00:07:34.399 --> 00:07:36.190 align:middle line:84%
was to bring the quality
of awe and wonder.

00:07:36.190 --> 00:07:38.840 align:middle line:84%
He felt God had given him that
capacity for awe and wonder.

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:40.850 align:middle line:90%
He realized how unusual it was.

00:07:40.850 --> 00:07:42.880 align:middle line:84%
And he felt that since
God had given it to him,

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:44.600 align:middle line:84%
that made it his
obligation to give it

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:46.121 align:middle line:90%
to his fellow human beings.

00:07:46.121 --> 00:07:47.870 align:middle line:84%
What does that have
to do with technology?

00:07:47.870 --> 00:07:49.090 align:middle line:90%
The Oculus Rift.

00:07:49.090 --> 00:07:51.420 align:middle line:84%
The Oculus Rift
is this big thing

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:54.560 align:middle line:84%
that you wear on your head
that creates a total 3D

00:07:54.560 --> 00:07:55.920 align:middle line:90%
virtual environment.

00:07:55.920 --> 00:07:58.810 align:middle line:84%
So you're no longer just doing
shoot-'em-up games in the wars

00:07:58.810 --> 00:08:00.850 align:middle line:84%
in the jungles of
Vietnam, you are there.

00:08:00.850 --> 00:08:02.730 align:middle line:84%
You are surrounded
by this thing.

00:08:02.730 --> 00:08:04.240 align:middle line:84%
All my friends in
the tech community

00:08:04.240 --> 00:08:06.060 align:middle line:90%
are talking about it right now.

00:08:06.060 --> 00:08:08.000 align:middle line:90%
Think about this for a second.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:09.450 align:middle line:90%
You walk down the street.

00:08:09.450 --> 00:08:14.499 align:middle line:84%
You're in LA or Portland,
Oregon, or here in Colorado.

00:08:14.499 --> 00:08:16.540 align:middle line:84%
And you decide to get on
the phone with a friend.

00:08:16.540 --> 00:08:19.030 align:middle line:84%
You've just had an emotionally
disturbing thing happen.

00:08:19.030 --> 00:08:21.000 align:middle line:84%
Your best friend
is in Beijing, just

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:22.250 align:middle line:90%
temporarily for a year or two.

00:08:22.250 --> 00:08:23.490 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure, but gone.

00:08:23.490 --> 00:08:25.110 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Yeah, you
get on the phone

00:08:25.110 --> 00:08:27.480 align:middle line:84%
and you talk to your
friend in Beijing.

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:29.850 align:middle line:84%
You realize what
evolution, what nature

00:08:29.850 --> 00:08:31.980 align:middle line:84%
would have had to go through
to give you the powers

00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:34.460 align:middle line:84%
to speak over a
distance of 12,000 miles

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:36.549 align:middle line:84%
and to hear what's going
on on the other end?

00:08:36.549 --> 00:08:37.830 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It would not have
happened in evolution,

00:08:37.830 --> 00:08:39.913 align:middle line:84%
unless we did it telepathically,
of course, right?

00:08:39.913 --> 00:08:41.539 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Well, it
happened through us.

00:08:41.539 --> 00:08:45.130 align:middle line:84%
Evolution evolved us, and
we evolved these machines.

00:08:45.130 --> 00:08:49.080 align:middle line:84%
But these machines not only give
astonishing new powers to us,

00:08:49.080 --> 00:08:51.040 align:middle line:84%
they give astonishing
new powers to the cosmos.

00:08:51.040 --> 00:08:54.280 align:middle line:84%
Now, that seems like a slightly
overblown statement, right?

00:08:54.280 --> 00:08:56.320 align:middle line:84%
Well, this cosmos has
already invented things

00:08:56.320 --> 00:08:58.750 align:middle line:84%
like atoms and
galaxies, and stars.

00:08:58.750 --> 00:09:00.900 align:middle line:90%
And then it invented you and me.

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:02.880 align:middle line:84%
And now that it's
invented through us.

00:09:02.880 --> 00:09:06.800 align:middle line:84%
Now that it's invented
the iPhone and the iPad,

00:09:06.800 --> 00:09:10.790 align:middle line:84%
that's given the cosmos itself
astonishingly new powers.

00:09:10.790 --> 00:09:13.930 align:middle line:84%
And since this cosmos is
all about the process--

00:09:13.930 --> 00:09:15.340 align:middle line:90%
we call it evolution.

00:09:15.340 --> 00:09:17.190 align:middle line:84%
But it's the process
of discovering

00:09:17.190 --> 00:09:20.140 align:middle line:84%
her own possibilities,
discovering her own potential.

00:09:20.140 --> 00:09:23.120 align:middle line:84%
And she discovers it through
the creatures that she creates.

00:09:23.120 --> 00:09:25.625 align:middle line:84%
And then those creatures in
turn discover new possibilities

00:09:25.625 --> 00:09:28.320 align:middle line:84%
that upset and
upend her old ways.

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:30.410 align:middle line:84%
Nature is all about
changing herself.

00:09:30.410 --> 00:09:32.530 align:middle line:84%
Nature is all about
reinventing herself.

00:09:32.530 --> 00:09:34.670 align:middle line:84%
Nature is all about
hoisting herself up

00:09:34.670 --> 00:09:36.190 align:middle line:90%
by her own boot laces.

00:09:36.190 --> 00:09:37.940 align:middle line:84%
And she does it
through you and me.

00:09:37.940 --> 00:09:40.720 align:middle line:90%
So does nature want technology?

00:09:40.720 --> 00:09:42.680 align:middle line:84%
You bet, because
nature's always out

00:09:42.680 --> 00:09:45.090 align:middle line:84%
for the next radical
reinvention of herself.

00:09:45.090 --> 00:09:47.000 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I've got six
grandchildren, Howard.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:47.500 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:09:47.500 --> 00:09:48.480 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: That is
amazing, George.

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:49.980 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --two of them lived
in my Saint Louis house.

00:09:49.980 --> 00:09:50.563 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yeah?

00:09:50.563 --> 00:09:53.480 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: My son moved back
from Las Vegas with his wife

00:09:53.480 --> 00:09:56.110 align:middle line:84%
starting his new
career, doing very well.

00:09:56.110 --> 00:09:57.480 align:middle line:90%
But they needed a place to stay.

00:09:57.480 --> 00:09:57.710 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Right.

00:09:57.710 --> 00:09:59.626 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So they stay
at good old dad's place.

00:09:59.626 --> 00:10:02.570 align:middle line:84%
So I've got a two-year-old and
a four-year-old living there.

00:10:02.570 --> 00:10:04.920 align:middle line:84%
And when I'm there,
they're there.

00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:07.300 align:middle line:84%
And they come running
into my room-- papa,

00:10:07.300 --> 00:10:11.420 align:middle line:84%
papa, papa, tickle me, tickle
me, jump on me, all that stuff.

00:10:11.420 --> 00:10:17.360 align:middle line:84%
But I've noticed that they
have understood technology.

00:10:17.360 --> 00:10:20.070 align:middle line:90%
They walk around with iPads.

00:10:20.070 --> 00:10:23.319 align:middle line:84%
And the little two-year-old
uses her mother's smartphone.

00:10:23.319 --> 00:10:24.110 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Fantastic.

00:10:24.110 --> 00:10:25.776 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And she's
playing little games.

00:10:25.776 --> 00:10:27.810 align:middle line:84%
She knows where all
the buttons are.

00:10:27.810 --> 00:10:31.070 align:middle line:84%
And it is absolutely
amazing watching

00:10:31.070 --> 00:10:33.430 align:middle line:90%
them go through this scenario.

00:10:33.430 --> 00:10:35.960 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: But here's something
you really have to realize.

00:10:35.960 --> 00:10:38.960 align:middle line:84%
We are born with twice as many
neurons, twice as many nerve

00:10:38.960 --> 00:10:41.190 align:middle line:90%
cells in our brain as we need.

00:10:41.190 --> 00:10:41.800 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:10:41.800 --> 00:10:43.980 align:middle line:84%
Because over the course
of the first four years

00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:47.720 align:middle line:84%
or so, the cells that are used
and the cell assemblies that

00:10:47.720 --> 00:10:50.480 align:middle line:84%
are used, they will
stick around vigorously.

00:10:50.480 --> 00:10:51.690 align:middle line:90%
They'll have vigorous health.

00:10:51.690 --> 00:10:51.980 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:10:51.980 --> 00:10:54.120 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: The ones that aren't
used, that aren't tapped.

00:10:54.120 --> 00:10:54.570 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They shrivel up.

00:10:54.570 --> 00:10:55.810 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: They die.

00:10:55.810 --> 00:10:57.982 align:middle line:84%
It's called apoptosis,
pre-programmed cell death.

00:10:57.982 --> 00:10:59.190 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Unless they're used.

00:10:59.190 --> 00:11:00.430 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Unless they're used.

00:11:00.430 --> 00:11:03.910 align:middle line:84%
Now, when you give a child
an iPhone or an iPad,

00:11:03.910 --> 00:11:07.170 align:middle line:84%
cell assemblies are being used
that were never used before.

00:11:07.170 --> 00:11:08.650 align:middle line:84%
So those, the cell
assemblies that

00:11:08.650 --> 00:11:10.890 align:middle line:84%
are staying alive and
becoming part of the brain

00:11:10.890 --> 00:11:13.530 align:middle line:84%
are cell assemblies that
in their own peculiar way

00:11:13.530 --> 00:11:16.860 align:middle line:84%
were never used before in
the history of mankind, which

00:11:16.860 --> 00:11:20.770 align:middle line:84%
means that by the time your
grandkids are six years old,

00:11:20.770 --> 00:11:24.600 align:middle line:84%
they have brains utterly unlike
yours, utterly unlike mine,

00:11:24.600 --> 00:11:26.900 align:middle line:84%
utterly unlike any of
the brains that have ever

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:29.190 align:middle line:84%
existed on the face of
planet Earth before.

00:11:29.190 --> 00:11:31.912 align:middle line:84%
The technology has
become like fingernails--

00:11:31.912 --> 00:11:33.370 align:middle line:84%
a part of their
body, a prosthetic.

00:11:33.370 --> 00:11:33.995 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It is.

00:11:33.995 --> 00:11:35.020 align:middle line:90%
And it's made them grow.

00:11:35.020 --> 00:11:35.380 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yeah.

00:11:35.380 --> 00:11:37.320 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's probably why
they're better at it than I

00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:37.750 align:middle line:90%
am--

00:11:37.750 --> 00:11:38.510 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: There's
another little fact.

00:11:38.510 --> 00:11:40.460 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --because those
cells are gone for me, right?

00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:42.250 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Well,
there's a simple fact

00:11:42.250 --> 00:11:44.184 align:middle line:84%
that there are books
like "The Shallows"

00:11:44.184 --> 00:11:45.850 align:middle line:84%
that say that all
these technologies are

00:11:45.850 --> 00:11:46.890 align:middle line:90%
dumbing our kids down.

00:11:46.890 --> 00:11:48.235 align:middle line:84%
Once upon a time there
was a philosopher

00:11:48.235 --> 00:11:49.350 align:middle line:90%
who said the same thing.

00:11:49.350 --> 00:11:51.330 align:middle line:90%
It was 300-400 BC.

00:11:51.330 --> 00:11:53.170 align:middle line:84%
And he said, these
new technologies

00:11:53.170 --> 00:11:54.807 align:middle line:90%
are going to dumb kids down.

00:11:54.807 --> 00:11:55.890 align:middle line:90%
What was he talking about?

00:11:55.890 --> 00:11:56.390 align:middle line:90%
Books.

00:11:56.390 --> 00:11:57.182 align:middle line:90%
His name was Plato.

00:11:57.182 --> 00:11:59.181 align:middle line:84%
So this complaint's has
been around a long time.

00:11:59.181 --> 00:12:00.556 align:middle line:84%
But if you give
the average dummy

00:12:00.556 --> 00:12:02.139 align:middle line:84%
in the street, the
average high school

00:12:02.139 --> 00:12:03.800 align:middle line:84%
kid that we think
has been dumbed down,

00:12:03.800 --> 00:12:06.890 align:middle line:84%
give a whole hundred of
them, a Stanford-Binet IQ

00:12:06.890 --> 00:12:11.396 align:middle line:84%
test from 1900, they will
register as marginal geniuses.

00:12:11.396 --> 00:12:12.520 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yes, that's right.

00:12:12.520 --> 00:12:16.220 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Because they've been
given an extra 35 points in IQ

00:12:16.220 --> 00:12:18.392 align:middle line:84%
over the course of
the last 114 years.

00:12:18.392 --> 00:12:20.225 align:middle line:84%
And we've done that in
Western civilization.

00:12:20.225 --> 00:12:22.040 align:middle line:84%
And we don't realize
that we've done it.

00:12:22.040 --> 00:12:23.290 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Is that a good thing?

00:12:23.290 --> 00:12:24.480 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: It's a wonderful thing.

00:12:24.480 --> 00:12:26.230 align:middle line:84%
It's a tremendous
thing, because you've

00:12:26.230 --> 00:12:29.510 align:middle line:84%
got 7 billion people
on planet Earth today.

00:12:29.510 --> 00:12:32.950 align:middle line:84%
Paul Ehrlich in 1968,
the Stanford biologist,

00:12:32.950 --> 00:12:36.150 align:middle line:84%
said that the population bomb
was going to kill us all.

00:12:36.150 --> 00:12:38.490 align:middle line:84%
Well, the population
bomb has enriched us all,

00:12:38.490 --> 00:12:40.900 align:middle line:84%
because the more brains
you bring into the process,

00:12:40.900 --> 00:12:43.510 align:middle line:84%
the faster the
creative growth goes,

00:12:43.510 --> 00:12:45.730 align:middle line:84%
and the more of
these vast upheavals,

00:12:45.730 --> 00:12:49.140 align:middle line:84%
like the iPhone and the iPad
take place in a lifetime,

00:12:49.140 --> 00:12:53.090 align:middle line:84%
and the more nature ends up
expanding her own capabilities.

00:12:53.090 --> 00:12:57.380 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Why is it that I
sense right now that humankind

00:12:57.380 --> 00:13:02.810 align:middle line:84%
is ticked off, not
happy, upset, concerned,

00:13:02.810 --> 00:13:04.395 align:middle line:90%
road rage is at a record high.

00:13:04.395 --> 00:13:05.020 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Right.

00:13:05.020 --> 00:13:06.840 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What is
going on with people?

00:13:06.840 --> 00:13:07.600 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Well there
are a couple of things.

00:13:07.600 --> 00:13:08.720 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I sense it,
and you sense it.

00:13:08.720 --> 00:13:11.219 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Well, we've talk about
it very frequently on "Coast

00:13:11.219 --> 00:13:11.940 align:middle line:90%
to Coast."

00:13:11.940 --> 00:13:13.420 align:middle line:84%
First of all, we,
humans are built

00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:15.460 align:middle line:84%
with a chronic
sense of discontent.

00:13:15.460 --> 00:13:17.560 align:middle line:84%
No matter what we've got,
it isn't good enough.

00:13:17.560 --> 00:13:18.750 align:middle line:84%
One day I was
sitting with one of

00:13:18.750 --> 00:13:20.280 align:middle line:84%
these precocious
nine-year-olds, who

00:13:20.280 --> 00:13:23.770 align:middle line:84%
was part of the iPad and
cell phone generation,

00:13:23.770 --> 00:13:25.926 align:middle line:84%
and we were
discussing this issue.

00:13:25.926 --> 00:13:27.300 align:middle line:84%
Can you imagine
that discussing--

00:13:27.300 --> 00:13:28.300 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You and
a nine-year-old?

00:13:28.300 --> 00:13:28.970 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Right.

00:13:28.970 --> 00:13:30.760 align:middle line:84%
And he said, "Wait, I got
to show you something."

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:32.551 align:middle line:84%
And he shows me the
intro to "The Jetsons."

00:13:32.551 --> 00:13:37.350 align:middle line:90%
["THE JETSONS" THEME SONG]

00:13:37.350 --> 00:13:40.380 align:middle line:84%
And he says, "See, these
people are in the 21st century

00:13:40.380 --> 00:13:43.250 align:middle line:84%
and they've got everything
that we ever dreamed of having.

00:13:43.250 --> 00:13:45.814 align:middle line:84%
And because it's ordinary to
them, it's nothing to them."

00:13:45.814 --> 00:13:46.730 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's nothing.

00:13:46.730 --> 00:13:48.313 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: And they're
still discontent.

00:13:48.313 --> 00:13:50.620 align:middle line:84%
And it's a nine-year-old
who is telling me

00:13:50.620 --> 00:13:52.210 align:middle line:84%
this piece of
philosophy, George.

00:13:52.210 --> 00:13:54.210 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And I
love "The Jetsons."

00:13:54.210 --> 00:13:56.020 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Well, so
but the message

00:13:56.020 --> 00:13:59.190 align:middle line:84%
is one of the great
things that drives us,

00:13:59.190 --> 00:14:02.470 align:middle line:84%
one of the things we need to
be grateful for is discontent,

00:14:02.470 --> 00:14:04.240 align:middle line:84%
discontent with
ourselves, discontent

00:14:04.240 --> 00:14:05.240 align:middle line:90%
with our surroundings.

00:14:05.240 --> 00:14:07.350 align:middle line:84%
Now, something different
with road rage,

00:14:07.350 --> 00:14:08.350 align:middle line:90%
because there you have--

00:14:08.350 --> 00:14:10.266 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yeah, but the
discontent has changed.

00:14:10.266 --> 00:14:13.300 align:middle line:84%
It's become more
than discontent.

00:14:13.300 --> 00:14:18.440 align:middle line:84%
It's become-- your discontent
is that striving to learn more

00:14:18.440 --> 00:14:22.690 align:middle line:84%
to be better that I like this
job, but I want a better one.

00:14:22.690 --> 00:14:25.040 align:middle line:84%
I'm sensing a different
kind of discontent.

00:14:25.040 --> 00:14:31.340 align:middle line:84%
I'm sensing a discontent
of bitterness, of anger.

00:14:31.340 --> 00:14:33.362 align:middle line:90%
And I can't put my finger on it.

00:14:33.362 --> 00:14:34.820 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: There is
something that we

00:14:34.820 --> 00:14:36.650 align:middle line:84%
haven't talked about
on "Coast to Coast."

00:14:36.650 --> 00:14:39.880 align:middle line:84%
And that is America needs
a vision transplant.

00:14:39.880 --> 00:14:44.010 align:middle line:84%
People need very deeply to have
something transcendent to feel

00:14:44.010 --> 00:14:46.040 align:middle line:84%
that there is something
bigger than themselves

00:14:46.040 --> 00:14:47.650 align:middle line:90%
that they are striving for.

00:14:47.650 --> 00:14:49.390 align:middle line:90%
That's a vital human need.

00:14:49.390 --> 00:14:51.380 align:middle line:84%
And in Western
civilization today, we

00:14:51.380 --> 00:14:53.660 align:middle line:84%
assume that people are
motivated by money.

00:14:53.660 --> 00:14:57.380 align:middle line:84%
No, money is a minor
motivation compared to status

00:14:57.380 --> 00:14:59.287 align:middle line:90%
